did.unittitle: New York State Society for Clinical Social Work Records
did.abstract: Established in 1968 to assist clinical social workers in performing their duties, the New York State Society for Clinical Social Work (NYSSCSW) offers professional support to its members in the practice of clinical psychotherapy. The collection documents the founding, administration, and activities of the NYSSCSW and its various local chapters.
did.physloc: The materials are located onsite in the department.

acqinfo.head: Acquisition Information
acqinfo.p: The first set of records in this collection were transferred to the University Libraries, M.E. Grenander Department of Special Collections and Archives in 2006. In November 2021, Marsha Wineburgh donated 14 additional boxes of material.

bioghist.head: Historical Note
bioghist.p: Contained is material concerning the New York State Society for Clinical Social Work (NYSSCSW), an organization founded in 1968 to address growing needs for professional support for private practitioners and to assist in navigating insurance reimbursement issues. Emerging at the same time as a number of other state clinical societies, the NYSSCSW is one of the founding charters of the National Federation of Societies for Clinical Social Work, which in 1971 united the New York chapters with counterparts from Louisiana, California, and Illinois under a shared mission of national advocacy, interstate communication, and the passing of licensing and insurance reimbursement legislation in all 50 states.

The legislative achievements of the Society include the defeat of legislation that would require the supervision of clinical social workers by a psychologist or psychiatrist, the passage of a bill in 1977 that would allow for the reimbursement of clinical social workers by insurance companies who covered other mental health services at the request of the client – the so called "P" law - and a further amendment to that legislation in 1984 which made the equal reimbursement of clinical social workers mandatory for any insurance plan that covered mental health services – the so called "R" law. 2002 saw the accomplishment of the Society's greatest effort yet with the passage of a formal licensure system for clinical social workers in New York. Since then, the NYSSCSW has continued to represent the interests of mental health practitioners in all levels of government, offering education and support to clinical social workers throughout the state.

In addition to advocating for clinical social workers through legislative efforts, the Society also conducts annual education conferences to instruct colleagues on the newest methods for the practice as well as publishing a biannual newsletter, The Clinician.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The collection consists of the New York State Society for Clinical Social Work newsletter, legislative files, material documenting lobbying activity, administrative records, and subject files including a amount of material about programming and events.

arrangement.head: Arrangement of the Collection
arrangement.p: The collection is organized into four series all organized chronologically. The first series contains administrative records pertaining to the organization. The second series contains legislation and various lobbying efforts conducted on behalf of the Society. The third series contains publications from the Society and its various local chapters, and the fourth contains materials from events organized by the Society and local chapters as well as information for members regarding the navigation of managed care.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains files from the tenure of the Society's former presidents Marsha Wineburgh (1980-1981, 2012-2015), Hillel Bodek (2004-2007), and David Phillips (1992-1993); meeting minutes from the New York State Board for Social Work; documents concerning the incorporation of the society and its bylaws; and materials from the New York Board of Regents Professional Practice Committee.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains legislative reports, drafts, and lobbying efforts conducted on behalf of the NYSSCSW throughout its history. Much of the collection concerns the campaigns to establish the "P" and "R" laws as well as the society's efforts to establish a formal license for clinical social workers. Materials from the society's legislative efforts regarding mental health practitioners are also included.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains copies of the society's newsletter – later known as "The Clinician" – dating back to 1974, as well as publications circulated by local chapters. The NYSSCSW newsletters often contain a President's Message, ACE Foundation News, information on continuing education programs, Committee and Chapter reports, plus clinical articles and book reviews.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains programs and fliers from events organized by the NYSSCSW and various local chapters, plus materials on the society's professional assistance to its members regarding the treatment of patients under managed care.
